{% from "project-status.njk" import projectStatus %}

<section id="overview" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="mission">Mission</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>Web Components</strong> extends the native Custom Elements API with patterns for scoped registries, dependency injection integration, and element lifecycle enhancements.
        Rather than replacing the browser's component model, we build directly on top of it.
    </p>
    <p>
        The project addresses three gaps in the standard Custom Elements API:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Scoped Registries:</strong> Allow multiple versions of a component to coexist without name collisions (aligns with the <a href="https://github.com/WICG/webcomponents/blob/gh-pages/proposals/Scoped-Custom-Element-Registries.md">Scoped Custom Element Registries proposal</a>).</li>
        <li><strong>Injector Integration:</strong> Custom elements resolve dependencies from the <a href="/projects/webinjectors/">Web Injectors</a> hierarchy instead of relying on global state or module scope.</li>
        <li><strong>Transient Components:</strong> Custom elements that replace themselves with semantically correct native HTML — solving the "dynamic tag" problem without permanent wrapper nodes.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="scoped-registries" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="scoped-registries-heading">Scoped Registries</h3>
    <p>
        The standard <code>customElements.define()</code> is a global, one-time operation. Two libraries defining <code>&lt;my-button&gt;</code> will collide.
        Scoped registries solve this by tying element definitions to a Shadow DOM scope.
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
// Each Shadow DOM root can have its own registry
const registry = new CustomElementRegistry();
registry.define('my-button', LibAButton);

class AppShell extends HTMLElement {
    constructor() {
        super();
        this.attachShadow({
            mode: 'open',
            registry // This shadow root uses LibA's button
        });
    }
}
    {% endhighlight %}

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(99, 102, 241, 0.05); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid var(--color-primary); margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="scoped-status" style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--color-primary); font-size: 1rem;">Standards Status</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            Scoped Custom Element Registries are a <strong>Stage 2 WICG proposal</strong> with Chrome implementation behind a flag.
            Web Plugs provides a polyfill that follows the proposal's API shape. When the standard ships, the polyfill becomes a no-op.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="injector-integration" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="injector-integration-heading">Injector Integration</h3>
    <p>
        Custom elements typically rely on module scope, global variables, or manual event dispatching to access shared services.
        With <a href="/projects/webinjectors/">Web Injectors</a>, components resolve dependencies from the DOM tree:
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
class UserCard extends HTMLElement {
    connectedCallback() {
        // Resolve services from ancestor injectors
        const userService = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(this, 'services:user');
        const theme = InjectorRoot.getProviderOf(this, 'customContexts:theme');

        this.innerHTML = `<h3 style="color: ${theme.primary}">${userService.name}</h3>`;
    }
}
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p>
        This follows the same pattern as Angular's hierarchical DI and React's Context — but it works with <strong>any</strong> custom element, not just those from a specific framework.
    </p>
</section>

<section id="transient-components" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="transient-components-heading">Transient Components</h3>
    <p>
        A <strong>Transient Component</strong> is a custom element that replaces itself with a semantically correct native HTML element during initialization.
        The transient element exists only long enough to determine <em>what</em> to render — then it disappears, leaving no wrapper node in the DOM.
    </p>

    <table>
        <tr><th>Problem</th><th>Framework Solution</th><th>Web Everything Solution</th></tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Heading level depends on nesting</td>
            <td>React: HeadingLevelContext + useContext</td>
            <td><code>&lt;auto-heading&gt;</code> resolves level from InjectorRoot, replaces itself with <code>&lt;hN&gt;</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Link vs button depends on href</td>
            <td>Vue: <code>&lt;component :is="tag"&gt;</code></td>
            <td><code>&lt;smart-link&gt;</code> replaces with <code>&lt;a&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;button&gt;</code></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>Dynamic element tag at runtime</td>
            <td>Svelte: <code>&lt;svelte:element this={tag}&gt;</code></td>
            <td>Any <code>TransientElement</code> subclass: resolves tag, transfers attributes &amp; children, self-replaces</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <h4 id="self-replacement-lifecycle">Self-Replacement Lifecycle</h4>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>connectedCallback fires</strong> — custom element is in the DOM</li>
        <li><strong>Determine replacement</strong> — read attributes, query injector chain, compute target tag</li>
        <li><strong>Create &amp; populate</strong> — <code>document.createElement(tag)</code>, transfer attributes and children</li>
        <li><strong>Schedule replacement</strong> — <code>queueMicrotask(() => this.replaceWith(el))</code></li>
        <li><strong>Microtask runs</strong> — transient element is removed, native element takes its place. Zero visual flash.</li>
    </ol>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
class TransientElement extends HTMLElement {
    connectedCallback() {
        const tag = this.resolveTag();
        const el = document.createElement(tag);

        for (const { name, value } of this.attributes) {
            if (!name.startsWith('data-transient-')) el.setAttribute(name, value);
        }
        el.append(...this.childNodes);

        queueMicrotask(() => this.replaceWith(el));
    }

    resolveTag(): string {
        throw new Error('resolveTag() must be implemented');
    }
}
    {% endhighlight %}

    <h4 id="use-cases">Concrete Use Cases</h4>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Element</th><th>Replaces With</th><th>Logic</th></tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>&lt;auto-heading&gt;</code></td>
            <td><code>&lt;h1&gt;</code>&ndash;<code>&lt;h6&gt;</code></td>
            <td>Heading level from injector or DOM nesting depth</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>&lt;smart-link&gt;</code></td>
            <td><code>&lt;a&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;button&gt;</code></td>
            <td>Presence of <code>href</code> attribute</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>&lt;field-group&gt;</code></td>
            <td><code>&lt;fieldset&gt;</code> + <code>&lt;legend&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;div&gt;</code></td>
            <td>Presence of <code>legend</code> attribute</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>&lt;icon name="..."&gt;</code></td>
            <td><code>&lt;svg&gt;</code></td>
            <td>Resolves SVG from icon registry</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><code>&lt;for-each&gt;</code></td>
            <td>Comment markers + repeated content</td>
            <td>Ergonomic directive syntax</td>
        </tr>
    </table>

    <p style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        See the full specification on the <a href="/blocks/transient-component/">Transient Component</a> block page, including AutoHeading code examples, SSR strategies, and pitfalls.
    </p>
</section>

<section id="safari" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="safari-constraints">Safari &amp; Customized Built-ins</h3>
    <p>
        Safari refuses to implement the <code>is=""</code> attribute for customized built-in elements.
        This is a hard constraint that shapes the project:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Autonomous elements only.</strong> All Web Everything custom elements use autonomous registration (<code>class MyEl extends HTMLElement</code>), never <code>customElements.define('my-el', MyEl, { extends: 'div' })</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Transient Components</strong> are the portable alternative to <code>is=""</code> — an autonomous element that becomes a native element via self-replacement.</li>
        <li><strong>Web Directives</strong> uses <code>&lt;template is="for-each"&gt;</code> with a polyfill from <a href="/projects/webplugs/">Web Plugs</a> for Safari.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="ssr" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="ssr-contract">SSR Contract</h3>
    <p>
        This section defines the server-side rendering contract for <strong>Web Components</strong>.
        Custom elements have three distinct SSR strategies depending on their type: standard components with Shadow DOM,
        light DOM components, and transient components that self-replace.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-server-output">Server Output Requirements</h4>
    <div class="comparison-table-wrapper mt-4">
        <table class="comparison-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Component Type</th>
                    <th>Server Output HTML</th>
                    <th>Notes</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Shadow DOM component</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;my-card&gt;
  &lt;template shadowrootmode="open"&gt;
    &lt;style&gt;...&lt;/style&gt;
    &lt;h2&gt;Title&lt;/h2&gt;
    &lt;slot&gt;&lt;/slot&gt;
  &lt;/template&gt;
  Slotted content here
&lt;/my-card&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server MUST emit Declarative Shadow DOM (<code>&lt;template shadowrootmode="open"&gt;</code>). Browser attaches shadow root during HTML parsing — no JS needed for initial render.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Light DOM component</strong></td>
                    <td>
<pre style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.8em;"><code>&lt;user-card&gt;
  &lt;h3&gt;John Doe&lt;/h3&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;john@example.com&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/user-card&gt;</code></pre>
                    </td>
                    <td>Server emits the custom element tag with its rendered children. Content is visible before upgrade.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Transient component</strong><br><span class="text-xs text-gray-500">(server-computed)</span></td>
                    <td><code>&lt;h2&gt;Section Title&lt;/h2&gt;</code></td>
                    <td>Server computes the replacement directly. No custom element tag in output. This is the <strong>recommended</strong> strategy.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Transient component</strong><br><span class="text-xs text-gray-500">(annotated fallback)</span></td>
                    <td><code>&lt;auto-heading data-level="2"&gt;Title&lt;/auto-heading&gt;</code></td>
                    <td>Server emits the custom element with a data annotation. Client upgrades to <code>&lt;h2&gt;</code>. Use when server cannot compute the replacement.</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>Scoped registries</strong></td>
                    <td>Correct tag names per scope in output</td>
                    <td>Server MUST resolve scoped registry lookups and use the correct element names for each shadow root's scope.</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>
    </div>

    <h4 id="ssr-hydration-expectations">Client Hydration Expectations</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>DSD parsing:</strong> Declarative Shadow DOM is automatically parsed by the browser — the shadow root exists before any JS runs. Client calls <code>customElements.define()</code> to upgrade the element and attach behavior.</li>
        <li><strong>No re-render on upgrade:</strong> If the server output matches the component's expected render, <code>connectedCallback</code> SHOULD detect the existing DSD content and skip re-rendering.</li>
        <li><strong>Transient no-op:</strong> If the server emitted the native element directly (server-computed strategy), transient component hydration is a no-op — the element is already correct.</li>
        <li><strong>Attribute transfer:</strong> For annotated transient components, the client reads <code>data-level</code> (or equivalent) and replaces the custom element with the native element, transferring all attributes except <code>data-transient-*</code>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4 id="ssr-progressive-baseline">Progressive Enhancement Baseline</h4>
    <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">
        With zero JavaScript: DSD components render their shadow DOM content (styles and markup visible).
        Light DOM components display their children as normal HTML.
        Server-computed transient elements are native HTML — fully accessible.
        Annotated transient fallbacks show pre-upgrade HTML with ARIA annotations
        (e.g., <code>&lt;auto-heading role="heading" aria-level="2"&gt;</code>) for screen reader support.
    </p>

    <h4 id="ssr-client-only">Client-Only Features</h4>
    <ul class="list-disc ml-6 text-gray-600 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Element lifecycle:</strong> <code>connectedCallback</code>, <code>disconnectedCallback</code>, <code>attributeChangedCallback</code></li>
        <li><strong>Property setting:</strong> JavaScript properties, method calls, imperative APIs</li>
        <li><strong>Scoped registry polyfill:</strong> Runtime polyfill for scoped <code>customElements.define()</code></li>
        <li><strong>Injector resolution:</strong> <code>InjectorRoot.getProviderOf()</code> for dependency injection</li>
        <li><strong>Dynamic element creation:</strong> <code>document.createElement()</code> with custom elements</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="comparison-block" style="background: rgba(251, 191, 36, 0.1); padding: 1.25rem; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #f59e0b; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
        <h4 id="ssr-implementor-note" style="margin-top: 0; color: #d97706; font-size: 1rem;">Implementor Note</h4>
        <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">
            This contract defines compliance requirements. The build system or server framework
            is responsible for emitting Declarative Shadow DOM, computing transient replacements,
            and resolving scoped registry lookups.
            Web Components does not ship an SSR runtime — it ships this specification.
            See also: the <a href="/blocks/transient-component/">Transient Component</a> block page for detailed SSR strategies.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="standards" class="section-card">
    <h3 id="web-standards">Web Standards Alignment</h3>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Use It</th></tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_Components/Using_custom_elements">Custom Elements v1</a></td>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td>Foundation for all components. Autonomous elements only (Safari constraint).</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Web_Components/Using_shadow_DOM">Shadow DOM</a></td>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td>Style encapsulation, slot-based content projection, scoped registry host.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/template">HTML Templates</a></td>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td>Inert content instantiation. Structural directives use <code>&lt;template&gt;</code> as authoring format.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="https://github.com/nicolo-ribaudo/tc39-proposal-structs">Scoped Custom Element Registries</a></td>
            <td>Stage 2 Proposal</td>
            <td>Per-shadow-root element definitions. Polyfilled in Web Plugs.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Element/replaceWith">Element.replaceWith()</a></td>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td>Core mechanism for transient component self-replacement.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/queueMicrotask">queueMicrotask()</a></td>
            <td>Baseline</td>
            <td>Safe lifecycle deferral for transient element replacement.</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
</section>